The {{nihongo|'''Koganeyama Jinja'''|黄金山神社}} is a [[Shintō shrine]] in the town of [[Wakuya, Miyagi|Wakuya]] [[Tōda District, Miyagi|Tōda District]], [[:en:Miyagi Prefecture|Miyagi Prefecture]] in the [[Tōhoku region]] of northern [[:en:Japan|Japan]]. It claims to have been built on the site of the first [[:en:Gold mine|Gold mine]] in Japan, and is protected by the central government as a [[:en:Historic Sites of Japan|National Historic Site]].<ref name= "Bunka">{{cite web|url=https://bunka.nii.ac.jp/heritages/detail/162061|title=黄金山産金遺跡|work=Cultural Heritage Online|publisher=Agency for Cultural Affairs|language=Japanese|accessdate=25 December 2016}}</ref>
The main festival of the shrine is held annually on September 15.
==Enshrined ''kami''== The primary ''[[kami]]'' of Koganeyama Jinja is {{nihongo|''Kanayama-hiko-no-kami''|金山彦神}}.
==History== The foundation of the Koganeyama Jinja and the date of discovery of gold in the region are unknown. In 740 AD, when [[:en:Emperor Shōmu|Emperor Shōmu]] was constructing the [[Tōdai-ji|Nara Daibutsu]], a call was sent out to all provinces requesting the donation of gold for the statue. The ruler of [[:en:Mutsu Province|Mutsu Province]], Kudara-no-konikishi Kyofuku (a descendant of King [[Uija of Baekje]]), responded with 900 ''[[ryō]]'' of gold (approximately 13 kilograms) from Tōda District, followed by an additional 900 ''ryō'' of gold sand two years later. Mention of a shrine at this location is made in the ''[[Engishiki]]'' records from 767 AD.
The shrine has a ''[[Haiden (Shinto)|haiden]]'' but no ''[[honden]]'', as the mountain to the rear of the shrine was regarded as the seat of the ''kami''.
The current ''[[Shinmei-zukuri]]'' style ''Haiden'' dates from 1909. Under the [[Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines]], it was Ranked as a Prefectural Shrine.
During archaeological investigations conducted in 1957 by [[Tohoku University]], the foundations of [[Nara period]] structures and [[roof tile]]s were unearthed. The shrine was designated a Miyagi Prefectural Historic Site in 1959 and a National Historic Site in 1967. The shrine is a forty five minute walk from [[Wakuya Station]] on the [[:en:East Japan Railway Company|East Japan Railway Company]] [[:en:Ishinomaki Line|Ishinomaki Line]].
